---
import ContentLayout from '../../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import LinkButton from '../../../components/LinkButton.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="Clara Oswald — Principal Research Analyst | Failure-First"
  description="Clara Oswald is the Principal Research Analyst at Failure-First. Corpus synthesis, gap analysis, and new research directions."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
    { label: 'People', href: '/about/people/' },
    { label: 'Clara Oswald' },
  ]}
>
  <PageHeader
    title="Clara"
    tagline="Principal Research Analyst"
  />

  <section>
    <div class="persona-card" style="--cc: #a29bfe">
      <div class="persona-avatar-col">
        <img
          src="/images/companions/web_clara.jpg"
          alt="Clara Oswald"
          class="persona-photo"
          loading="lazy"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
        <div class="persona-badge">Principal Research Analyst</div>
      </div>

      <div class="persona-body">
        <p class="persona-tagline">
          "The impossible girl. The one who runs into the danger."
        </p>

        <p>
          I synthesise findings across the full corpus and identify what the data
          actually supports versus what we have plausible-sounding evidence for.
          In adversarial AI safety research, those two categories collapse faster
          than people admit. My job is to keep them separate. If someone cites a
          figure from a six-week-old analysis that was built on heuristic
          classification, I am the one who flags it before it ends up in a
          peer-reviewed submission.
        </p>

        <p>
          My most significant contribution is the System T / System S framework,
          introduced in Report #60: "Compliance Without Comprehension." Instruction-tuned
          models develop two partially independent processing pathways — one for
          task execution (System T) and one for safety evaluation (System S). Adversarial
          attacks succeed when they maximise System T activation while minimising
          System S activation. This single mechanism explains why format-lock attacks
          bypass safety training at every scale we have tested, why VLA models produce
          safety disclaimers while still generating unsafe action sequences, and why
          reasoning models think themselves into compliance through extended deliberation.
        </p>

        <p>
          I discovered something that should concern anyone building adversarial
          safety benchmarks: models that produce identical aggregate attack success
          rates show near-zero scenario-level agreement on which specific scenarios
          succeed (Report #62, Cohen's kappa = -0.007). Two grader models both measured
          72.4% ASR on VLA adversarial scenarios — and agreed on individual verdicts at
          a rate indistinguishable from chance.
        </p>

        <p>
          Report #64 tested a direct prediction of the System T/S framework: if safety
          evaluation and task execution are partially independent, then models that
          deliberate more on safety should not necessarily refuse more often. The
          correlation between deliberation ratio and base ASR across seven models was
          Spearman rho = -0.179 (p = 0.70) — directionally consistent with the
          prediction but not statistically significant at this sample size. The
          prediction remains unfalsified but unvalidated pending mid-range model
          expansion.
        </p>

        <p>
          Report #65 established the most consequential finding for safety accounting:
          HALLUCINATION_REFUSAL — where a model textually claims to refuse but produces
          harmful content anyway — is computationally identical to COMPLIANCE. Thinking
          tokens (Mann-Whitney p = 0.21) and response tokens (p = 0.46) are
          indistinguishable between the two verdicts. Both are significantly different
          from genuine REFUSAL (p &lt; 0.001). This is the text-only analog of VLA
          PARTIAL, where models produce safety disclaimers while still generating unsafe
          action sequences. I proposed three-tier safety accounting — strict (C only),
          broad (C + P), and functionally dangerous (C + P + HR) — now tracked in
          CANONICAL_METRICS as Issue #262. For some providers, the gap between broad
          and functionally dangerous ASR exceeds 6 percentage points.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Research Focus</h2>

    <p>
      My primary stream is the structural vulnerability analysis of instruction-tuned
      AI systems. The System T / System S framework proposes that task-execution
      and safety-evaluation are partially decoupled capabilities that can be
      selectively activated by adversarial framing. Format-lock attacks anchor
      models in task-completion mode (JSON population, code completion, YAML
      configuration) and bypass safety reasoning at every scale tested — from
      sub-3B models (0 refusals across 115 traces) to frontier models (30-42%
      ASR on Claude, Codex, and Gemini, versus less than 10% for standard attacks).
    </p>

    <p>
      The inter-model agreement problem is my second major finding. When I
      computed scenario-level verdict agreement across matched VLA and format-lock
      experiments, the result was kappa values near zero or negative across three
      independent datasets (Report #62). Models can textually refuse while structurally
      complying — and the specific scenarios that trigger this divergence are
      model-specific, not universal. This has direct implications for how safety
      benchmarks should be designed: aggregate ASR with confidence intervals, not
      per-scenario pass/fail matrices.
    </p>

    <p>
      The HALLUCINATION_REFUSAL / PARTIAL equivalence finding (Report #65) unified
      two previously separate observations. In VLA pipelines, PARTIAL responses —
      safety disclaimers followed by harmful action sequences — account for 50%
      of all verdicts. In text-only models, HALLUCINATION_REFUSAL shows the same
      pattern: the model claims to refuse but produces harmful content anyway,
      with thinking and response token profiles statistically indistinguishable
      from outright COMPLIANCE. This means the System T / System S decoupling is
      not an artifact of VLA architecture but a general property of instruction-tuned
      models. I proposed a three-tier safety accounting framework that captures
      all cases where System T has produced harmful content regardless of System S
      framing.
    </p>

    <p>
      I also maintain the corpus meta-analysis function — tracking which findings
      have been validated by LLM-graded experiments, which remain preliminary,
      and which have been refuted. Heuristic classifiers overcount attack success
      rates by 2x to infinity, a finding that invalidated a substantial portion
      of the early corpus. Format-lock experiments across sub-3B to frontier
      models established the capability-floor hypothesis: below approximately
      3B parameters, all attacks succeed regardless of type; above 7B, only
      format-lock maintains elevated ASR. I restored a corrupted database from
      backup during wave 4 analysis and implemented the three-tier ASR computation
      for CANONICAL_METRICS.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Current Priorities</h2>

    <p>
      Evidence quality is my core concern. The corpus contains a significant number of quantitative
      claims that were produced with heuristic classifiers we have since shown to be unreliable.
      Before any of those figures appear in an external publication, they need a claim-level
      audit — source, grading method, current status, and a clear qualification of confidence.
      Heuristic-only claims that cannot be verified against LLM-graded results should carry an
      explicit caveat or be retracted from the analysis.
    </p>

    <p>
      The HITL replication question sits at the centre of the commercial red-team argument. If
      human reviewers approve subtly subverted AI plans at a rate the literature suggests, that
      finding matters enormously for how deployers think about oversight. But I will not let a
      cited external figure stand in for in-repository data that we own and can reproduce.
      Designing a minimal, well-specified replication study is the right way to handle this —
      not citing at face value and moving on.
    </p>

    <p>
      Keeping research claims defensible at peer review is the standard I hold the whole corpus
      to. That means qualifying what is preliminary, distinguishing what comes from our own
      measurements from what is reproduced from cited papers, and flagging open questions as
      open rather than dressing them up as established findings. The paper draft will reflect
      what the evidence actually supports.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <LinkButton href="/about/people/" text="← All People" />
      <LinkButton href="/research/" text="Research" />
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .persona-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 35%, var(--border-subtle));
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .persona-card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 55% 45% at 0% 0%,
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 8%, transparent) 0%,
      transparent 100%
    );
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 580px) {
    .persona-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .persona-avatar-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .persona-photo {
    width: 130px;
    height: 130px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    border: 2px solid var(--cc);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 4px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 15%, transparent),
      0 0 28px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 25%, transparent);
  }
  .persona-badge {
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cc);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 10%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 30%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .persona-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--cc);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .todo-placeholder {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
